text: If only the Chinese trusted themselves more to break internationally. Their vision is wrong, hiring foreign A-list actors aren't going to help one bit, them looking out of place will put off fans no matter how big they are, a great foreign director would have served better.  Zhang Yimou is great, he's got his own unique style, sometimes he breaks into foreign box offices, sometimes not, but he should stick to it without the need of foreign superstars. We just need more directors like him with their own identity it doesn't always need to be fantasy or artsy with the colours.  Since Chinese cinema are saturated with fantastical elements, maybe they should give a more realistic but just as dramatic epic a try.  Basically no Wuxia and no try-hard action like overcomplicated showy manoeuvres (like horses running on armies of men holding their shield up), just something dramatic in the realm of believabilty.  Like for instance, a director should have their own interpretation of the rescue of Liu Bei's son by Zhao Yun by having him breaking into lines of low quality troops with a unit of his personal crack guards(Alexander-Darius), *NOT* singlehandedly Dynasty-warrioring it by killing 20 men with one swoop of his spear. And lines of enemy shouldn't be taking literally, like lines and lines of troops in formation, just behind enemy lines.  Oh, how I wish to watch a chinese epic in the style of Gladiator or Kingdom of Heaven. (without the same old chinese actors)

text: The Great Wall was built more than 2000 years ago during China's first dynasty Qin. It's definitely true GW wasn't built for defending dragon, neither was it for defending Mongolians, well at least not its original purpose. There were several nomads attempting to invade China in the past 2000 years including Huns, Turks etc.   By the time of 13th century AD when Genghis Khan led Mongolians came into power, the northern part of China had already been conquered and ruled by Manchurians and Khitans for more than 300 years. So technically, Great Wall didn't perform its functional role.   After Ming dynasty took China back from Mongolians, the emperor started to rebuild the Great Wall far southern to its original border. So the Great Wall you see in Beijing today is what we Chinese called "Ming Chang Cheng" meaning "Great Wall in Ming Dynasty". The original "Qin Chang Cheng" site is in today's Inner Mongolia, most of which has already been deserted.
